iif evaluates its condition function at subscription time. If the condition returns truthy, it subscribes to the first observable; otherwise it subscribes to the second. The condition runs once per subscription, so each subscribe picks fresh.

```typescript
import { iif, of, Observable } from "rxjs";

let flag = false;
const on$: Observable<string> = of("on");
const off$: Observable<string> = of("off");

const toggle$: Observable<string> = iif(() => flag, on$, off$);

toggle$.subscribe((v: string) => { void v; });
flag = true;
toggle$.subscribe((v: string) => { void v; });
```

A ternary like cond ? a$ : b$ is evaluated eagerly at pipeline-construction time; that means both branches are captured when the ternary runs. iif(() => cond, a$, b$) defers the decision until each subscription, so the condition can reflect fresh state and neither branch's side effects fire until we actually subscribe to the chosen one.

