import { concat, merge, zip, of, Observable, map } from "rxjs";

const a$: Observable<number> = of(1, 2, 3);
const b$: Observable<number> = of(10, 20, 30);

const concatenated$: Observable<number> = concat(a$, b$);
const merged$: Observable<number> = merge(a$, b$);
const zipped$: Observable<number> = zip(a$, b$).pipe(
  map(([x, y]: [number, number]) => x + y)
);

concatenated$.subscribe((v: number) => { void v; });
merged$.subscribe((v: number) => { void v; });
zipped$.subscribe((v: number) => { void v; });
```

concat subscribes to each source in order â€” only after source N completes does N+1 start. merge subscribes to all sources immediately and interleaves emissions as they arrive. zip pairs the Nth emission from every source and emits a tuple once every source has produced N values, completing when any source completes.

```typescript
import { concat, merge, zip, of, Observable } from "rxjs";

const x$: Observable<string> = of("x1", "x2");
const y$: Observable<string> = of("y1", "y2");

const seq$: Observable<string> = concat(x$, y$);
const mix$: Observable<string> = merge(x$, y$);
const pair$: Observable<[string, string]> = zip(x$, y$);

seq$.subscribe((v: string) => { void v; });
mix$.subscribe((v: string) => { void v; });
pair$.subscribe((p: [string, string]) => { void p; });
```

concat is for strict sequencing: use it when operation B must not start until operation A has completed (e.g. run migration scripts in order). merge is for fire-and-forget parallelism: both sources subscribe immediately and their emissions interleave. If A is slow, merge lets B's values show up first; concat would hold them back.

